reviews.text: Awesome place. Excellent food paired with excellent drinks and awesome atmosphere. Love coming here as many TV's with the latest sports on. Try some of their specialty beers.
Very nice patio but I prefer the esplanade location for their dance floor. This spot only really has seating. Beer is good. Food is not.
Decent food + unmatched variety of beers

Food is ridiculously small portioned. We asked for smoked gouda on the $22 charcuterie board and got one slice of it.

 Merchant burger ( wagyu beef supposedly) overcooked, tastes like a normal burger, that was $25. Fries that came with the meal were broken in half and not the full fry.

A couple of the beers I wanted were also not available. 

Ordered oysters. They put a dozen oysters on s bed of full ice cubes... So a lot of the juice spilled out. Amateurs.

Onion rings ordered, I had a full onion ring made with the outside hard layer of the onion that should have been thrown out because you can't even chew it.

Small portions, food isn't great, expensive for what it is. No care taken in giving high quality food but the scraps ( outside onion layer and scrap fries that were broken and overcooked burger)
So muchhhh food. It was finger licking!

adr_address: 145 John St, Toronto, ON M5V 2E4, Canada
formatted_address: 145 John St, Toronto, ON M5V 2E4, Canada
name: The Ballroom

reviews.text:
Horrible food. I have been here for two private company events and several times as a regular customer and had the same experience. During one of the events chicken skewers were served RAW on the inside. Another time we came back and one of my colleagues ordered a veggie burger on a gluten free bun. The burger came back on a regular white bun and was so overcooked that she would not cut through it. Server apologized and agreed to give her a new order, which AGAIN came back on a white bun and overcooked. Unbelievable. 

I will say however, the venue itself is fine, just need to get a new chef and kitchen staff. Just go for the drinks.

Was here this past Friday for a birthday. No cover for a 'club' was nice, and $3 coat check was cheaper than areas around. The live music was awesome, both quality and music choices. Between bowling, Ping Pong and the club portions make it seem like a cool hang out area. Drink were expensive through ($9 for a Sam Adams).

All ways a fun time. The place is a bit pricey but that is expected because of location. The food options are quite nice with a big selection of great appetizers. The bowling is pretty great too. Would recommend for groups of friends.

Poor experience here. Ordered the steak sandwich medium rare; it came out well done. Stood at the bar longer than I should have for the bartender to come around. But try using the ping-pong or foosball tables and the staff would pop up quickly to remind you that it's not available for use despite no one else playing. Other half of our party went to bowl and they received minimal service until it was time to get kicked off.

Pros: Nice place to hang out. Just had a Christmas Party there. There is a separate section for parties with 2 separate bowling alleys, 2 pool tables and a separate bar.

Cons: When it was time to leave, we were rudely asked to leave because of another party coming in. 

Food and Drinks: Drinks are reasonable for downtown ($7.00 + tip for a rum and coke). Finger foods were ok but not spectacular.

Great food

Great food! Nice casual atmosphere. Fantastic live bands! 30+ age group.

Sorry but the waitress was rushing me to place an order and it wasn't even busy. I asked the waitress what is the customers choice and she couldnt even suggest anything from their ripped up menu. The place is called Jake's boathouse and they only had haddock for fish and chips and it was the worst fish and chips I ever had. If you enjoy fish and chips do not order it, its so disgusting, the batter was raw. I was being polite to stay and I will never go back.

Service was slow, I didn't get my steak dinner til after 9pm; when the waiter finally brought my dinner it was cold. I had the same order last year and it was way better. Maybe it might make a difference if I received my order right when it was plated.
Great food, good portions, well priced, lots of beer options on tap.  Homey and fun place to eat.  Also supports live music and has a stage (a rarity among restaurants).

Had an awful experience. I go to the Keg at least 2-3 times a month at all different locations. For this to be one of their few flagship locations I was very disappointed. Not only did both appetizers get screwed up but it took 50 minutes for dinner. And then my Husband's steak was rare instead of Medium how the heck can it be rare after 50 minutes. reviews.text:
I've been to Marlowe's several times in the past for dinner as well as for work holiday functions. This year, I had the opportunity to organize my department's holiday party and it turned out to be great--thanks for the great service provided by the staff at Marlowe.

I was quite impressed as I hadn't been to the restaurant in at least 3 years prior to last night. The food was good and we had approximately 53 guests served with a three course meal. Although the chicken was somewhat bland, the steak was moist and pasta was flavourful.  The mushroom soup and salads were also hits!

The atmosphere was great. They permitted the use of their projector throughout the evening for our slide show and a DJ was brought in by the restaurant at around 10pm so that our guests could dance. All in all, a great place to host an event. We will definitely consider this for future work events.

Special thanks to the floor and event managers who helped facilitate this event. They were very friendly and provided exceptional service.

We have our office Christmas dinner at the restaurant.  But the food is quite disappointing especially the seafood and whisky.  The seafood seemed like they have been frozen for ages and not defrosted properly before putting them into the oven.  They are rubbery and have no seafood taste.  The sauce was so salty that I could not finish the whole thing.  I can understand that this is the busiest time of the year, yet the quality of the service and food cannot be sacrificed.  We have ordered the chicken with vegetable soup.  But all orders came out with different portions and different amount of chicken and vegetables.  Some had too much chicken and vegetables while some had nothing but clear broth.  Also, we asked for water, but they gave us sparkling water instead.  We, of course, need to pay for that.  They insisted that they gave us 2 bottles but I could only see one bottle of sparkling water on the table.  
My overall opinion is that the only good thing about the restaurant is the bread they serve as they are right out of the oven.

The Marlowe is a great restaurant with amazing and friendly staff. Everyone in our party raved about the food especially the perfectly cooked steak! I will definitely be back to the Marlowe for more delicious food and drinks! Would recommend to anyone for a group gathering, event, simple date night or later in the evening with the dance floor, a party night out.

Thanks again to all the staff at the Marlowe for making my dad's retirement such a great success. Steven was so helpful and accommodating, worked with me to make sure the night was so great

Nice play to eat dinner. A bit loud as sound travels very easily throughout the building. Although I was there with a corporate group for lunch, I feel like the waiters and waitresses could do no harm by smiling and being more welcoming. 

The food was decent, steak and chicken choices were moist, while the salmon and the rigotini was a little underwhelming. The mushroom soup appetizer was much tastier than the salad. For dessert, the chocolate lava cake was nice, but a little hard on the outside.

We hosted an engagement brunch for our son and future daughter-in-law for 110 guests last weekend at Marlowe's.  The entire experience was first class, start to finish!  We did our planning with Steven, who was totally accommodating and flexible.  The event was managed by Yuri, who was amazing; whatever we asked was done immediately.  The menu was very complete (we did the kosher style brunch) and we had nothing but compliments from our guests.  And to top it off, the pricing was extremely reasonable...  you could pay that price at any venue just to go for a walk-in brunch, never mind getting an entire restaurant to yourself.  As you can tell, we were totally happy with the experience, and would recommend it to anyone looking for a low fuss, well priced celebration.

I'm posting this review on behalf of my girlfriend, on as many forums as we can, so that people reading it know what an awful place this is: 

It took me over a year to finally review this place because I was waiting to recover from the horror that was my boyfriend and I's dining experience at La Societe. 

We made a reservation for 7:00 pm on a week night expecting that it will not be busy and the service would be better as servers would be more attentive if they had fewer tables. I was wrong. 

We were not greeted for 15 minutes even though several servers walked by the table and the restaurant was maybe ten percent full. Eventually, a man named Mike approached us to take a drink order. It was very short and abrupt followed by him disappearing for another 10 minutes. He finally pours the wine we ordered and left before we could get a word in. 

I placed a piece of gum on a side plate so that I could drink the wine. When Mike came back to take away the appetizer plates, he took the plate away and said "you shouldn't put your gum on the plates, it's rude". Perhaps if he didn't neglect our table for 25 minutes, I could have asked for a napkin. I've worked in the service industry before and I've never come across such ignorant service. We were taken aback but didn't want to let his attitude ruin our night and we decided to try the food we already ordered anyway. 

The main course was terrible. My boyfriend’s scallops were over-cooked and under seasoned and my meal made for a bland eating experience. Mike was rude and not attentive for the rest of the evening, doing the bare minimum to make us feel welcome. I am not one to send food back but I actually would have done so this time if we didn't want to rush and leave this establishment. The vibe we got from the meal was that this is food prepared by people who are inexperienced and unskilled but find themselves in a restaurant that wants to bill itself as a classy, fine dining experience. The food tasted like it didn’t want to be there. 

When we were finished our meal, my boyfriend told Mike that he was inappropriate in his comment to me and that he should apologize. He responded that he “isn't apologizing, that I'm rude for leaving my gum on the plates" and added, "if you are upset you can talk to my manager,” like it was common for people to complain to the manager here.

When we spoke to the manager, a guy named Zia, he said "well the plates are expensive. Are we done here?" We paid the bill and left.

In years of going out and dining in Toronto, neither my boyfriend nor I have ever been treated with this level of rudeness. I'm not sure what made this place so sub-par, perhaps the lack of training and respect for paying customers or the mediocre cuisine, but we will never return.

reviews.text: It's no wonder that Jacob's is truly a top  steak places in Toronto. They've covered all the aspects of a remarkable steakhouse - delicious, impeccably prepared steaks (and sides!), interactive Caesar salad, excellent wine and cocktail selection. Finally, the service, as someone with 8 years of hospitality service experience, is absolutely perfect. Jeez, even the post-meal take home MUFFINS are amazing. I would highly recommend this steakhouse to someone inquiring.

The steak is cooked to the perfection! Period. I have never seen medium and medium rare plus both prefect throughout whole steak like this. Never in Ruth's nor the Keg. Service is great, no question about it. Only think is the steak portion is all quite large. Sides are the only disappointments. We tried; of them, not one impressed us. But being able to order half of portion is pretty sweet.  I would suggest get one App, one steak to share, several half sides, and two desserts. That should be great dinning without great damage.

Simply its going to be your best steak experience. delicious food that melts in your mouth with tasty appetizers and their famous cesar salad. don't miss that one. You have to constantly ask to pass it to you or just eat without sauce... I am glad that I tried this place but I question if I ever come back.

A carnivore's dream. Simply the best steak house in the city, don't be fooled by large chains and other high end restaurant whom sell steak as a possible main. Jacob's main menu is 95% steak!  The selection spans the world from local Canadian offerings to the undisputed Japanese wagyu champions. Let's not forget that Jacobs is actually certified to sell and prepare Kobe beef! One of the few in North America! A massive wine list to fit all tastes, pairing choices can be recommended by your waiter. Save room for dessert as they are a great finish to a divine night. A special note, that the friendly waiters are knowledgeable, so ask as many questions as you want! I recommend splitting some Japanese wagyu, multiple 4oz of different variations allow you to taste the vast difference between them and you own main! I recommend Jacobs to any steak lover, see and taste the difference in the cuts and types of beef. My first visit opened my eyes and subsequent visits added to that experience!

name: Gardiner Museum

reviews.text: It's an open secret that the Gardiner is a great alternative to the ROM, especially if you're into ceramics, or not into crowds. Right across from the ROM, it's a smaller, more focused museum that offers great exhibits year round. Top floor is a rotating exhibit, 2nd floor is European/Asian and 1st floor is ancient/contemporary. Saw their 10 different new age Christmas trees last week for the first time which was cute. Definitely worth a visit for locals and tourists alike!
Amazing ceramics collection! Classes and drop-in times are offered here with highly qualified teachers for people who want to try. Beautiful gift-shop and excellent lecturers.

I always feel so invigorated and inspired when I leave the Gardiner Museum.  The museum has items on three floors, ranging from a wonderful collection of  Central/South American pieces to 20th century modern pieces.  The restaurant food is yummy, a bit pricey but the food is delicious.  

Best tip: The drop in classes on Friday and Saturday are both really popular, see their site for details.  The sign up system should be going online by end of 2016, I heard (not a moment too soon!)  But a great deal to see if you want to see if you're interested before signing up for an actual session. My son and I feel in love with potting with the wheel - so much fun.
A peaceful little gem. Always worth a visit and a sweet shop and cafe too.

Went to see the True Nordic exhibit, which was smaller than I expected but still full of great information and wonderful pieces, both original and contemporary. The rest of the museum is a treasure trove of pottery, and definitely worth the visit!
